Hi JB,

Thanks for clarifying. This is how I interpreted the call:

   - CURATING DATA FOR AI: Representing, managing, curating, and
   structuring scientific data for use in model training
   - BUILDING DATA ENDPOINTS FOR AI AGENTS: Developing benchmarks,
   standards, endpoints, or protocols that enable the use of open-source to=
ols
   within agentic workflows
   - CODE REFACTORING AND PERFORMANCE IMPROVEMENT FOR AI: Scalability and
   performance improvements, including support for hardware acceleration
   - INTEROPERABILITY TOOLS FOR AI: Interoperability frameworks that make
   tools composable within AI-driven pipelines

The all-caps wording above reflects my interpretation of the priorities
emphasized in the call.

My reading is that the RFA is primarily targeting mechanisms that make
scientific data, standards, and software ecosystems AI-ready. In other
words, the emphasis seems to be less on developing new agentic systems
themselves, and more on enabling existing data infrastructures and tools to
interface effectively with AI workflows and future AI agents.

Am I misinterpreting the scope of the call?

Looking forward to the discussion.

Franco


